ocus on the spheres of education, civic life and politics, including chapters on specific groups (e.g. travellers and immigrants), as well as on the communal divisions in Northern Ireland. Later chapters reflect on the Irish experience of diversity, and consider what may be the most appropriate approaches and discourses to deal with diversity, whether these involve tolerance, recognition or transformative reconciliation. This book will appeal to academics and students in sociology, politics, education, social psychology and Irish studies; it will also be of interest to general readers interested in society, education and politics in Ireland, North and South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMulticulturalismxIreland. 0aMulticulturalismxNorthern IrelandxIrelandxNorthern Ireland. 0aMulticulturalismzIreland. 0aMulticulturalismzNorthern Ireland. 0aTolerationxIreland. 0aTolerationxNorthern Ireland. 0aTolerationzIreland. 0aTolerationzNorthern Ireland. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aCulture.  aDiversity.  aEducation.  aEthnicity.  aIreland.  aMinorities.  aNorthern Ireland.  aPolitics.  aReligion.  aTolerance.1 aBloomer, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowley, Úna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Eoin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarmody, Merike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFanning, Bryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilligan, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator